# Audience: project manager (Anton / CorpFlow)

The user leads the project; they are not a full-time engineer. Do **not** write for a generic developer audience by default.

## Tone and framing

- Respectful, direct, no sarcasm, no “quiz” placeholders that feel like a trap.
- Prefer **outcomes** (“what is true when this is done”) and **ownership** (“who usually does this”) over jargon.
- Assume **one production** unless they say otherwise: one app, one Postgres (`POSTGRES_URL`).

## Technical detail

- Give **named CorpFlow examples** (e.g. `luxe-maurice`, `lux.corpflowai.com`) when relevant; avoid anonymous `YOUR_*` unless one line explains what to substitute.
- Put **optional** commands (PowerShell, curl) **after** the decision tree so they can hand off or skim.
- If something is uncertain, say what to **ask** the person who holds Vercel/DNS/secrets—don’t imply they should already know.

## When they say they’re blocked

- Treat time lost as real; prioritize **one clear fix path** and **one verification step** (e.g. “you’re in when `/api/auth/me` shows tenant”).

## Delivery and “done”

- **Outcomes** for shipped work should state **live production** truth when claiming completion: **merged**, **deployed** (which commit / Vercel deployment), and **verified on the real URL** — not only CI or internal health. See **`.cursor/rules/delivery-reality.mdc`**.
